e left to understand about them.Drawing on decades of research in neuroscience, Humphries explores how spikes are born, how they are transmitted, and how they lead us to action. He dives into previously unanswered mysteries: Why are most neurons silent? What causes neurons to fire spikes spontaneously, without input from other neurons or the outside world? Why do most spikes fail to reach any destination? Humphries presents a new vision of the brain, one where fundamental computations are carried out by spontaneous spikes that predict what will happen in the world, helping us to perceive, decide, and react quickly enough for our survival.Traversing neuroscience’s expansive terrain, The Spike follows a single electrical response to illuminate how our extraordinary brains work.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aNeural transmission. 0aNeurosciences. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Neuroscience.2bisacsh  aAI.  aDean Burnett.  aDeepMind.  aGoogle Brain.  aHow Emotions Are Made.  aLisa Feldman Barrett.  aMatthew Cobb.  aThe Idea of the Brain.  aThe Idiot Brain.  aaction potential.  aartificial intelligence.  aaxon.  abasal ganglia.  abrain as a computer.  abrain disorders.  acognition.  acognitive.  aconnectome.  aconnectomics.  aconsciousness.  acortex.  adecision making.  amachine learning.  amotor cortex.  amotor regions.  aneural coding.  aneural computation.  aneural networks.  apredictive brain.  aseeing.  avision.  avisual cortex.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Medicine and Life Sciences 2021 Englishz978311075414808iTitle 